sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER WINNING THE INNINGS.
West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons scored four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs to take the lead in the county championship in two days.
Their stay at the top may be short-lived, however, as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey came close to victory, while Kent made up for a rain-affected loss against Nottinghamshire.

After Somerset were bowled out for 83 at Grace Road in the opening match this morning, Leicestershire extended their first innings to 94 before being bowled out for 296, with Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Somerset, who were 213 behind, made a solid start to their second innings, but then Simmons stepped up and bowled them out for 174.
However, Essex look certain to regain top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such firmly dominated their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who was considered England's redundant one-day player, scored 158 hits, his first century in the Championship this season, as Essex scored 372 hits and led by 82 hits in the first innings.
By the close Yorkshire had turned this into a 37-run advantage, but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes as he took four for 24 in 48 balls and left them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man England have dismissed, continued to silence his critics as he scored 80 points after going four for 45 on Thursday in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points, and Surrey finished with 429 points for seven, a 234-point advantage.

Derbyshire continued their chase for a first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, but they are still 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody got six for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a 233 lead in the first innings.
After a disappointing opening day when the weather had a big impact, Kent stepped up a gear and dismissed Nottinghamshire for 214.
Paul Johnson held them to 84 points, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague took four for 55.
By the start of the game, Kent had scored 108 points on three-pointers.

The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), succeeds Tony Adams, who captained the team at the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss the opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer took over the captaincy on a trial basis, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take over.
"I'm sure there won't be any problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was ready and really wanted to do it.
"It is very difficult to come to a 100% conclusion about something like this in four days.
but he knows how to behave, is respected by his teammates and knows the team situation, even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's partner at Euro 96, Teddy Sheringham, withdrew from the team on Friday due to injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

Romania beat Lithuania 2-1 (1-1 at half-time) in an Under-21 European football match on Friday.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS JAILED AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.
Rotor Volgograd must play their next home game behind closed doors as fans threw bottles and stones at Dinamo Moscow players on Saturday after the 1-0 defeat that briefly gave Rotor the league lead.
Anatoly Gorokhovsky, head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, said on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on 3 September.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of the UEFA Cup last year, was fined USD 1 000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position with 11 games to go.
Volgograd are three points behind Alania and two behind Dinamo Moscow, but they are a game ahead of the leaders and two behind the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMA'S ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran will step into the ring on Saturday and once again try to preserve his long-standing career.
The 45-year-old Duran will face little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in Panama City in a non-title super middleweight bout.
The fight, which will be Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, is described here as "the return of a legend", and Duran still talks like he's in his prime.
I will not retire," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer admit that the career of the boxer who has won championships in four different weight classes - light heavyweight, welterweight, middleweight and middleweight - is coming to an end.
"Every time he fights, he is at the last point of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could undermine his position as one of the world's greatest boxers," said Ramon Manzanares, President of the Panamanian Boxing Federation.
Duran, who has a 97-12 record over three decades, hopes a win in the 10-hour bout will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho won a controversial points decision against Panamco in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN SPRING DOUBLE WINS UNDER THE SPOTLIGHTS.
Andre Agassi avoided disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of upsets at the US Open.
The 11th seed from Washington failed to repeat his Wimbledon miracle comeback, losing to a red-hot Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in two hours and 51 minutes on Stadium Court.
On the next court, 10th seed Rios lost to another Wimbledon-related player - bad boy Jeff Tarang.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.

The day's programme went smoothly, although the sixth seed, former champion Agassi, had to pull himself out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit, having won 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the evening belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came back from 1:5 down in the Wimbledon semi-final against Todd Martin and two sets down in the third set, was ready for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title in New Haven two weeks ago, served for the win in the third set at 5:4 before Washington came back into the match.
"I kept telling myself, 'Give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept calm and was proud of myself, because normally I would have folded up my tent and gone home."
O'Brien, a former US college national champion, scored 17 aces and finally beat a relentless Washington.
The fifth set was on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand down the line, backhanded down the line to give O'Brien a 4:2 lead.
The Texan held serve for 5:2 with two aces and then used his eighth point to win the match when Washington found the net with another backhand for 40:0.
"You just keep fighting and trying to force him to play a little.
I think he was a bit cramped at some points," Washington said.
But I think he served well when he had to. "

Tarango, who was fined $28,000 and suspended from this year's All-England Club two years ago for a Wimbledon tantrum, argued with and taunted fans in the stands during a lively two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios.
The thunderous crowd supported the distracted Chilean and booed the burly American, who was eating up all the attention.
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was decided in the third set, which the American won 7-5, much to the disappointment of the spectators.
"I like to be booed by the audience every day.
It motivates me to play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I played my best tennis in college, when fraternities were throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Rios was not impressed by Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," says Rios."
But I don't think that's the case.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
I have lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I play American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel comfortable on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango gave the crowd sarcastic kisses, then swayed his body in front of Rios' fans and gave him a cheer.
"I share their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are rooting against me.
When I won, I thought I could dispel them a little. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the best offensive player in National Football League history at quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to line up over the middle, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham was selected to the Pro Bowl three times and passed for 4 482 yards on 677 passes.
"I want to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"Although I am sad to leave, I look forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise during his 11 years in Philadelphia and has brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia and across the NFL. "
Cunningham was selected in the second round in 1985 and completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a contract with the broadcaster.
